3
00:00:04,413 --> 00:00:05,710
No, no.

4
00:00:05,747 --> 00:00:06,941
With your serious money

5
00:00:06,982 --> 00:00:09,348
I could fiX you up
with a plan as a starter.

6
00:00:09,384 --> 00:00:12,353
You know,
I been meaning to ask you...

7
00:00:12,387 --> 00:00:15,948
but a guy my age hates
to ask a punk like you

8
00:00:15,991 --> 00:00:17,959
for tips on things.

9
00:00:17,993 --> 00:00:20,120
What do you own?

10
00:00:20,162 --> 00:00:21,390
What do I own?

11
00:00:21,430 --> 00:00:22,988
I own
two catcher's mitts

12
00:00:23,031 --> 00:00:24,726
and a baseball autographed

13
00:00:24,766 --> 00:00:27,997
by each and every member
of the New York Mammoths.

14
00:00:28,036 --> 00:00:29,298
Put it all together

15
00:00:29,338 --> 00:00:32,171
you got a fin
in any hock shop in Chicago.

16
00:00:32,207 --> 00:00:33,731
What I own is debts.

17
00:00:33,775 --> 00:00:35,333
Well, that's simple.

18
00:00:35,377 --> 00:00:37,368
We'll declare bankruptcy.

19
00:00:37,412 --> 00:00:40,210
That's something for a fellow
to look forward to.

20
00:00:40,315 --> 00:00:42,510
How?

21
00:00:42,551 --> 00:00:45,611
I'll show you, but you got
to do me one favor.

22
00:00:45,654 --> 00:00:46,882
What's that?

23
00:00:46,922 --> 00:00:49,117
You got to lay off Pearson.

24
00:00:49,157 --> 00:00:50,784
I just joke around.

25
00:00:50,826 --> 00:00:52,794
It's something
to keep up my spirits

26
00:00:52,828 --> 00:00:54,489
that's all.

27
00:00:54,529 --> 00:00:56,292
He's dying.

28
00:01:01,169 --> 00:01:03,034
You mean soon, any day now?

29
00:01:03,071 --> 00:01:05,130
Could happen
any time.

30
00:01:05,173 --> 00:01:06,834
Does Dutch know?

31
00:01:06,875 --> 00:01:10,242
No. You mustn't
tell him, either.

32
00:01:10,312 --> 00:01:12,405
He'd cut him loose in a minute.

33
00:01:12,447 --> 00:01:13,971
Only me and you know.

34
00:01:14,016 --> 00:01:15,540
Only you
and me know...

35
00:01:15,584 --> 00:01:17,575
only you and me
will ever know.

36
00:01:34,870 --> 00:01:36,601
Arthur?

37
00:01:36,738 --> 00:01:38,706
Arthur?

38
00:01:38,740 --> 00:01:40,537
Arthur? Arthur?

39
00:01:40,575 --> 00:01:42,133
Who is that?

40
00:01:42,177 --> 00:01:44,509
Arthur, Arthur,
something's happening.

41
00:01:44,546 --> 00:01:46,309
Something's happening to me.

42
00:01:52,421 --> 00:01:53,388
Yeah?

43
00:01:53,422 --> 00:01:54,946
Yeah? What's happening?

44
00:01:54,990 --> 00:01:56,753
Where's Goose? I need help.

45
00:01:56,792 --> 00:01:57,759
What for?

46
00:01:57,793 --> 00:01:58,919
You know.

47
00:01:58,960 --> 00:02:01,326
Well, what do I do?

48
00:02:01,363 --> 00:02:04,389
You can talk, Horse knows.

49
00:02:04,433 --> 00:02:05,491
He told me.

50
00:02:05,534 --> 00:02:08,002
You weren't supposed
to mention it.

51
00:02:08,036 --> 00:02:09,936
Only my roomie.

52
00:02:09,971 --> 00:02:12,940
You got to go get this doctor,
Dr. Charleston P. Chambers.

53
00:02:12,974 --> 00:02:13,963
Check.

54
00:02:18,280 --> 00:02:19,770
I'm really sorry
to have woke you.

55
00:02:19,815 --> 00:02:21,248
I was hoping it wouldn't happen

56
00:02:21,283 --> 00:02:22,250
at a bad hour.

57
00:02:22,284 --> 00:02:24,115
I was hoping it
wouldn't happen this...

58
00:02:24,152 --> 00:02:25,710
Make it back to me another time.

59
00:02:25,754 --> 00:02:27,722
No, there's not going to be
another time.

60
00:02:29,791 --> 00:02:32,885
Dutch'll probably bring
Piney Woods back up now

61
00:02:32,928 --> 00:02:36,489
and he's going to be real happy.

62
00:02:36,531 --> 00:02:38,499
Is the doctor going to come?

63
00:02:38,533 --> 00:02:39,522
Oh, yeah, yeah.

64
00:02:39,568 --> 00:02:40,762
Goose went after him.

65
00:02:40,802 --> 00:02:41,894
Goose? Why Goose?

66
00:02:41,937 --> 00:02:43,802
Why Goose?

67
00:02:43,839 --> 00:02:45,431
Well, he's right
down the hall.

68
00:02:45,474 --> 00:02:47,032
Goose has got
a heart of gold.

69
00:02:47,075 --> 00:02:48,042
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

70
00:02:48,076 --> 00:02:49,566
I guess it never
really showed.

71
00:02:52,481 --> 00:02:54,779
Probably you told him
or something.

72
00:02:54,816 --> 00:02:57,011
I nev... I never told a soul.

73
00:02:57,052 --> 00:02:58,019
Yeah...

74
00:02:58,053 --> 00:02:59,850
Probably everybody'd be nice
to you

75
00:02:59,888 --> 00:03:01,378
if they knew you were dying.

76
00:03:01,423 --> 00:03:04,551
Everybody knows
everybody's dying.

77
00:03:04,593 --> 00:03:06,754
That's why people are
as good as they are.

78
00:03:09,765 --> 00:03:12,359
I'm scared. Hold onto me.

79
00:03:23,945 --> 00:03:26,436
Who is
the sick baseball player?

80
00:03:28,717 --> 00:03:30,480
Are you
a baseball player, too?

81
00:03:30,519 --> 00:03:32,680
Yes, sir,
I'm Henry Wiggen, sir.

82
00:03:32,721 --> 00:03:34,188
Thank you.

83
00:03:34,222 --> 00:03:37,316
I've heard that name...
not that I follow the game.

84
00:03:37,359 --> 00:03:39,725
I've detested it
since early childhood.

85
00:03:39,761 --> 00:03:41,991
It's a dying game, I'm told.

86
00:03:42,030 --> 00:03:43,725
Hmm...

87
00:03:52,908 --> 00:03:54,239
Hmm...

88
00:03:58,380 --> 00:03:59,574
Mmm.

89
00:04:02,384 --> 00:04:05,876
Mmm. I think...

90
00:04:05,921 --> 00:04:07,684
I think it's something else.

91
00:04:07,722 --> 00:04:11,214
You mean something else besides
what they said in Minnesota?

92
00:04:11,259 --> 00:04:13,727
Oh, I couldn't say about that.

93
00:04:13,762 --> 00:04:14,854
I only mean that

94
00:04:14,896 --> 00:04:17,456
I don't think
there's any danger

95
00:04:17,499 --> 00:04:19,057
right at this minute.

96
00:04:19,100 --> 00:04:20,226
Oh, boy.

97
00:04:20,335 --> 00:04:21,734
'Cause this sure felt like it.

98
00:04:21,770 --> 00:04:25,171
Now you can do me one favor.

99
00:04:25,207 --> 00:04:26,333
Please send a bill

100
00:04:26,374 --> 00:04:29,002
care of my wife
in Perkinsville, New York

101
00:04:29,044 --> 00:04:30,739
and also not leak anything

102
00:04:30,779 --> 00:04:32,178
to the papers.

103
00:04:32,247 --> 00:04:33,612
I'm not in the habit

104
00:04:33,648 --> 00:04:36,776
of leaking my, uh, house calls
to the papers.

105
00:04:39,855 --> 00:04:42,517
Arthur, meet Mr. Rogers.

106
00:04:42,557 --> 00:04:45,526
Mr. Rogers is a detective.

107
00:04:45,560 --> 00:04:47,050
Sit down.

108
00:04:49,564 --> 00:04:51,794
Mr. Rogers has been
down to Bainbridge

109
00:04:51,833 --> 00:04:54,028
and is now on his way
up to Minnesota

110
00:04:54,069 --> 00:04:55,798
filling in some facts for me.

111
00:04:55,837 --> 00:04:57,862
However, you can save us
some time

112
00:04:57,906 --> 00:04:59,931
by filling in the rest
of the story

113
00:04:59,975 --> 00:05:01,636
which Mr. Rogers has begun.

114
00:05:01,676 --> 00:05:04,509
I'll certainly try my darndest.

115
00:05:06,548 --> 00:05:08,209
Tell him what you discovered.

116
00:05:08,316 --> 00:05:11,843
In Bainbridge, Georgia,
the subject's domicile

117
00:05:11,887 --> 00:05:14,754
I developed
the following information.

118
00:05:14,789 --> 00:05:19,021
I interviewed a Mr. Jay Clark,
the mailman

119
00:05:19,060 --> 00:05:21,358
and a colored woman named Janet.

120
00:05:21,396 --> 00:05:23,694
Uh, never mind the facts.

121
00:05:23,732 --> 00:05:25,165
Give me details.

122
00:05:25,233 --> 00:05:27,827
The details are
that the subject, Pearson

123
00:05:27,869 --> 00:05:31,032
told various people that he
wasn't feeling so good

124
00:05:31,072 --> 00:05:33,370
and went to the
hospital in Atlanta.

125
00:05:33,408 --> 00:05:35,899
The hospital in
Atlanta recommended

126
00:05:35,944 --> 00:05:37,969
the hospital
in Minnesota...

127
00:05:38,013 --> 00:05:40,641
If you'd actually spoken
to anybody worth the while

128
00:05:40,682 --> 00:05:43,173
you'd learn that Pearson has
this old-time habit

129
00:05:43,218 --> 00:05:44,583
of running back to Atlanta

130
00:05:44,619 --> 00:05:46,382
maybe once
or twice a month.

131
00:05:46,421 --> 00:05:49,822
No doubt you developed
that much.

132
00:05:49,858 --> 00:05:53,521
No need telling you
where he went in Atlanta...

133
00:05:53,562 --> 00:05:54,551
everybody knows that.

134
00:05:54,596 --> 00:05:55,563
Naturally.

135
00:05:55,597 --> 00:05:56,655
And you know

136
00:05:56,698 --> 00:06:00,964
what you sometimes pick up
in such places...

137
00:06:01,002 --> 00:06:02,629
which he did

138
00:06:02,671 --> 00:06:06,072
and which he'd rather not
have them treat in Atlanta

139
00:06:06,107 --> 00:06:09,042
so close to home,
for fear of it getting back

140
00:06:09,077 --> 00:06:10,874
and embarrassing his mother.

141
00:06:10,912 --> 00:06:13,813
So, up he goes to Minnesota
with his fishing gear

142
00:06:13,848 --> 00:06:17,511
forgetting that the ice is nine-
feet thick that time of year

143
00:06:17,552 --> 00:06:19,520
checks in with the Mayo Brothers

144
00:06:19,554 --> 00:06:22,421
gets himself shot
with a couple of miracle drugs

145
00:06:22,457 --> 00:06:24,482
flirts with the nurses,
checks out

146
00:06:24,526 --> 00:06:26,824
meets me in Cannon Falls,
we hunted...

147
00:06:26,861 --> 00:06:28,988
What? What?!

148
00:06:29,030 --> 00:06:31,464
We hunted up some girls we know.

149
00:06:31,499 --> 00:06:33,990
God... damn it.

150
00:06:34,035 --> 00:06:36,435
God... damn it!

151
00:06:39,407 --> 00:06:40,806
Hanson?

152
00:06:40,842 --> 00:06:42,571
Hanson!

153
00:06:42,611 --> 00:06:43,578
Loftus!

154
00:06:43,612 --> 00:06:44,772
Randy, get me Doc Loftus!

155
00:06:44,813 --> 00:06:46,144
What's the sudden
interruption?

156
00:06:46,181 --> 00:06:47,170
I don't know.

157
00:06:47,215 --> 00:06:48,910
You're the detective.

158
00:06:48,950 --> 00:06:51,145
I seen the girls
he runs around with.

159
00:06:51,186 --> 00:06:53,177
She'll give it
to the whole club.

160
00:06:53,221 --> 00:06:56,520
She'll run
right around my infield!

161
00:06:56,558 --> 00:06:58,753
Take down your pants.

162
00:06:58,793 --> 00:07:00,351
Are you over the clap yet?

163
00:07:00,395 --> 00:07:02,090
Oh, yes, sir; long ago.

164
00:07:02,130 --> 00:07:03,188
How do we know?

165
00:07:03,264 --> 00:07:04,561
Check him over, Doc.

166
00:07:04,599 --> 00:07:09,195
All I need is the clap running
through my ball club now!

167
00:07:09,237 --> 00:07:10,397
Hey, Arthur

168
00:07:10,438 --> 00:07:11,928
what's going on around here?

169
00:07:11,973 --> 00:07:15,067
Sometimes I don't know
what's going on, sometimes.

170
00:07:16,711 --> 00:07:19,202
He looks just fine to me.

171
00:07:19,247 --> 00:07:20,680
Never better.

172
00:07:20,715 --> 00:07:23,309
Healthy young man
if ever I saw one.

173
00:07:23,351 --> 00:07:24,909
Uh, should I head out

174
00:07:24,953 --> 00:07:27,581
and develop this
information farther

175
00:07:27,622 --> 00:07:29,487
in-in Rochester, Minnesota?

176
00:07:29,524 --> 00:07:31,116
Rochester, Minnesota?

177
00:07:31,159 --> 00:07:32,956
Where you got shot
for the clap.

178
00:07:32,994 --> 00:07:34,120
Oh, yeah, yeah.

179
00:07:34,162 --> 00:07:36,995
Stay with it.

180
00:07:37,032 --> 00:07:39,592
Some things have yet
to be eXplained.

181
00:07:39,634 --> 00:07:43,593
In July, we dropped a couple
more games off the pace.

182
00:07:43,638 --> 00:07:46,436
It was strange...
the team was going lousy

183
00:07:46,474 --> 00:07:48,669
yet I led both leagues
in wins...

184
00:07:48,710 --> 00:07:50,405
smelling 25, maybe more...

185
00:07:50,445 --> 00:07:52,777
and for the first time
in his life

186
00:07:52,814 --> 00:07:54,179
Bruce played regular.

187
00:07:54,282 --> 00:07:57,080
He didn't bust down fences
left and right

188
00:07:57,118 --> 00:07:59,848
but he hit steady... 265, 270.

189
00:07:59,888 --> 00:08:04,382
That's not great,
but for Bruce, it's fantastic.

190
00:08:04,426 --> 00:08:05,586
Wouldn't you say

191
00:08:05,627 --> 00:08:08,460
that if the Arcturis
Company discovered

192
00:08:08,496 --> 00:08:11,158
that you'd been
writing phony letters

193
00:08:11,199 --> 00:08:14,794
to prevent Bruce from
changing his beneficiary...

194
00:08:14,836 --> 00:08:16,997
Oh, that's not a phony letter;
that's a real letter.

195
00:08:17,038 --> 00:08:18,471
- You wrote it.
- The company wrote it.

196
00:08:18,506 --> 00:08:20,201
Or if you didn't write it

197
00:08:20,241 --> 00:08:22,801
your wife wrote it...
that's my guess...

198
00:08:22,844 --> 00:08:26,712
and several baseball players
tell me I'm probably right.

199
00:08:26,748 --> 00:08:31,651
Maybe I'll go check this
with the company themself.

200
00:08:31,686 --> 00:08:33,847
They'd take away your license.

201
00:08:33,888 --> 00:08:35,150
Throw me in jail, hmm?

202
00:08:35,223 --> 00:08:37,054
Ruin you as an
insurance agent.

203
00:08:37,092 --> 00:08:38,559
Hmm...

204
00:08:38,593 --> 00:08:41,926
Well, if you say anything
to the Arcturis Company

205
00:08:41,963 --> 00:08:46,024
I'll stroll down to a certain
police station on 66th Street

206
00:08:46,067 --> 00:08:47,898
and swear out
a complaint

207
00:08:47,936 --> 00:08:50,632
against a certain
"answering service."

208
00:08:50,672 --> 00:08:53,971
Well, I'm not really anXious
to complain

209
00:08:54,008 --> 00:08:56,033
to the Arcturis Company.

210
00:08:56,077 --> 00:08:59,274
I don't see any reason
why you and I can't...

211
00:08:59,314 --> 00:09:02,147
arrange a settlement of this
between us.

212
00:09:02,183 --> 00:09:03,150
A deal?

213
00:09:03,184 --> 00:09:04,481
A compromise.

214
00:09:04,519 --> 00:09:06,384
I can't compromise
with his money.

215
00:09:06,421 --> 00:09:07,820
That's none of your business.

216
00:09:07,856 --> 00:09:09,551
You're supposed
to do what he wants.

217
00:09:09,591 --> 00:09:11,752
I'm deciding what he wants.

218
00:09:11,793 --> 00:09:13,021
That's illegal.

219
00:09:13,061 --> 00:09:14,926
I know.

220
00:09:14,963 --> 00:09:19,832
First week in August,
his father hit town.

221
00:09:59,107 --> 00:10:01,405
Safe!

222
00:10:17,325 --> 00:10:18,849
Stee...

223
00:10:18,893 --> 00:10:22,886
All right, Mammoths,
let's go, let's go!

224
00:10:37,912 --> 00:10:39,470
Safe!

225
00:10:39,514 --> 00:10:43,416
Get a job, Wiggen,
get a job!

226
00:11:10,445 --> 00:11:13,039
All right, Arthur, it's
just one of those days.

227
00:11:13,081 --> 00:11:15,015
It's the last
of the order, Dutch.

228
00:11:15,049 --> 00:11:16,778
You've done a lot of pitching.

229
00:11:16,818 --> 00:11:18,251
Let somebody else mop up.

230
00:11:18,286 --> 00:11:21,119
Go ahead, take it easy.

231
00:11:23,391 --> 00:11:24,858
Let's get Caselli in here.

232
00:11:24,893 --> 00:11:26,884
Caselli!

233
00:11:35,236 --> 00:11:36,863
Oh, Henry.

234
00:11:36,905 --> 00:11:38,031
Hello, Mr. Pearson.

235
00:11:38,072 --> 00:11:40,870
Please, move on, and don't
disturb the ball players.

236
00:11:40,909 --> 00:11:42,035
That's okay, Jim.

237
00:11:42,076 --> 00:11:44,203
I know I am intruding
on you, and I know...

238
00:11:44,245 --> 00:11:45,212
No, you're not.

239
00:11:45,246 --> 00:11:46,713
You've been
intruded on enough.

240
00:11:46,748 --> 00:11:47,874
Aah...

241
00:11:47,916 --> 00:11:50,043
It's a ball game, sir.

242
00:11:50,084 --> 00:11:51,711
You win 'em; you lose 'em.

243
00:11:51,753 --> 00:11:56,053
No, Henry, I mean,
regarding my son.

244
00:11:56,090 --> 00:11:57,523
Sir?

245
00:11:57,558 --> 00:12:03,224
You know about...
the condition of my son?

246
00:12:03,264 --> 00:12:04,390
Yes, sir.

247
00:12:04,432 --> 00:12:06,059
Well, so do I.

248
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:09,160
Yes, sir, I suspected you did.

249
00:12:09,203 --> 00:12:13,230
How-How can he be so sick
and play so well?

250
00:12:13,308 --> 00:12:15,833
I really don't even know, sir.

251
00:12:15,877 --> 00:12:17,504
If I knew, I'd say.

252
00:12:17,545 --> 00:12:18,910
And not play so well

253
00:12:18,947 --> 00:12:21,848
but better than ever,
and that's a fact.

254
00:12:21,883 --> 00:12:23,282
That's a fact, sir.

255
00:12:23,318 --> 00:12:25,513
There's no mistake
about that.

256
00:12:25,553 --> 00:12:28,078
So, I've been wondering
if they didn't make

257
00:12:28,122 --> 00:12:31,057
some kind of a mistake
out there at that hospital

258
00:12:31,092 --> 00:12:32,059
in Minnesota

259
00:12:32,093 --> 00:12:34,027
because it-it's hard
to believe

260
00:12:34,062 --> 00:12:35,359
that it can be true.

261
00:12:35,396 --> 00:12:37,523
I-I, uh...

262
00:12:37,565 --> 00:12:40,534
I don't think
I'd count on it, sir.

263
00:12:40,568 --> 00:12:44,402
They got an awful famous
reputation up there.

264
00:12:44,439 --> 00:12:48,034
I know it's been
a terrible strain on you.

265
00:12:48,076 --> 00:12:49,737
It's a lot worse on him, sir

266
00:12:49,777 --> 00:12:51,745
and on you.

267
00:12:51,779 --> 00:12:54,748
So, I've been...
I've been thinking

268
00:12:54,782 --> 00:12:57,444
and I don't generally swear...

