00:17:26,854 --> 00:17:28,981
I told you I'd get
to the bottom of this!

363
00:17:29,023 --> 00:17:31,184
Good morning to all.

364
00:17:32,860 --> 00:17:35,192
Good morning.

365
00:17:37,198 --> 00:17:39,598
Shouldn't have kept
it a secret, Henry.

366
00:17:39,634 --> 00:17:41,568
I can't understand
why I'm not crying.

367
00:17:41,602 --> 00:17:43,934
Keep your hankie handy,
dearie.

368
00:17:43,971 --> 00:17:47,634
Makes you think it can happen
to your own son.

369
00:17:47,675 --> 00:17:49,643
It upset Joe
something terrible.

370
00:17:49,677 --> 00:17:51,611
Don't you think
we discussed it enough

371
00:17:51,646 --> 00:17:53,170
as far as how horrible it is?

372
00:17:53,214 --> 00:17:55,114
Tonight is another ball game
as usual.

373
00:17:55,149 --> 00:17:57,947
Maybe we can get help
from the, uh, commissioner.

374
00:17:57,985 --> 00:17:58,952
You can't get help there

375
00:17:58,986 --> 00:18:00,681
and keep it in this room
at the same time.

376
00:18:00,721 --> 00:18:02,018
Well, then let
the facts out.

377
00:18:02,056 --> 00:18:03,023
It wouldn't be human.

378
00:18:03,057 --> 00:18:05,184
Is it human to lose?

379
00:18:05,226 --> 00:18:06,625
We're calling in Piney Woods

380
00:18:06,661 --> 00:18:08,526
from Queens City
for eXtra catching.

381
00:18:08,562 --> 00:18:11,531
Ready on your call
to Professor Traphagen.

382
00:18:11,565 --> 00:18:13,294
Do we really need him?

383
00:18:13,334 --> 00:18:16,531
He was the greatest
catcher I ever saw.

384
00:18:16,570 --> 00:18:18,060
Arthur, you were his boy.

385
00:18:18,105 --> 00:18:20,699
You talk him into coming back
to help us.

386
00:18:20,741 --> 00:18:22,003
He's out of condition.

387
00:18:22,043 --> 00:18:23,943
He teaches English
at a college.

388
00:18:23,978 --> 00:18:26,344
He won't play.
He'll stick to catching.

389
00:18:26,380 --> 00:18:28,940
He'll study us, help
us make it to the end.

390
00:18:28,983 --> 00:18:30,473
How much can I offer him?

391
00:18:30,518 --> 00:18:32,986
The sky's the limit,
and I'm sure the boys will go

392
00:18:33,020 --> 00:18:34,612
to a full series share
if we win.

393
00:18:34,655 --> 00:18:35,986
Red?

394
00:18:36,023 --> 00:18:38,651
Oh, trouble, Red.

395
00:18:38,693 --> 00:18:40,160
Lots of trouble!

396
00:18:40,194 --> 00:18:42,822
Arthur wants to talk to you!

397
00:18:42,863 --> 00:18:46,355
Yeah, it's Arthur who got us
in trouble in the first place.

398
00:18:48,202 --> 00:18:52,434
Red, we got a crisis here,
and we need your help.

399
00:18:52,473 --> 00:18:56,000
You get a full series share
if we win it.

400
00:18:56,043 --> 00:19:00,173
Red, how do you like the sound
of a thousand dollars a week?

401
00:19:00,281 --> 00:19:02,875
Can't find a substitute?

402
00:19:02,917 --> 00:19:04,043
To do what?

403
00:19:04,085 --> 00:19:05,052
Teach English?

404
00:19:05,086 --> 00:19:07,054
What teach English?

405
00:19:07,088 --> 00:19:09,181
People speak English already!

406
00:19:09,223 --> 00:19:11,054
Red, Red, it's urgent.

407
00:19:11,092 --> 00:19:16,029
I swear you won't have to play,
just instruct the catching!

408
00:19:16,063 --> 00:19:17,530
Right!

409
00:19:17,565 --> 00:19:19,192
Hop on the nearest plane.

410
00:19:19,233 --> 00:19:20,723
Love and kisses, Red.

411
00:19:22,069 --> 00:19:23,559
I hate him.

412
00:19:23,604 --> 00:19:26,664
Have you thought up
anything yet, Doc?

413
00:19:26,707 --> 00:19:27,696
I'm thinking.

414
00:19:27,742 --> 00:19:29,437
You're a
slow thinker.

415
00:19:29,477 --> 00:19:31,069
This thing, this...

416
00:19:31,112 --> 00:19:32,636
What is it called?

417
00:19:32,680 --> 00:19:34,944
The disease is named
for Hodgkin.

418
00:19:34,982 --> 00:19:37,143
He's the man who identified it.

419
00:19:37,184 --> 00:19:38,310
Find him.

420
00:19:38,352 --> 00:19:39,819
Is he alive himself?

421
00:19:39,854 --> 00:19:41,651
Maybe he thought up a cure
by now

422
00:19:41,689 --> 00:19:44,954
that those jugheads up in
Minnesota didn't hear about yet.

423
00:19:44,992 --> 00:19:47,426
What the hell kind of a place
is that anyway

424
00:19:47,461 --> 00:19:50,396
to build a goddamn hospital
in the wilds of nowhere?

425
00:19:50,431 --> 00:19:52,058
Does a man freeze his ass off

426
00:19:52,099 --> 00:19:54,158
by the time they get him
down in bed?

427
00:19:54,201 --> 00:19:56,635
You. You were there.

428
00:19:56,670 --> 00:19:58,968
You sneaked out there
in the middle of winter

429
00:19:59,006 --> 00:20:00,871
and all the rest
was horse feathers.

430
00:20:00,908 --> 00:20:03,035
You and Mary "P" for palooka!

431
00:20:03,077 --> 00:20:07,309
And hunting through the ice
and miracle drugs for the clap

432
00:20:07,348 --> 00:20:09,441
and tricks on the telephone!

433
00:20:09,483 --> 00:20:11,815
Whoo-hoo!
Howdy, partners!

434
00:20:11,852 --> 00:20:13,012
Hey, Piney,
what's going on?

435
00:20:13,053 --> 00:20:14,850
Tumblin' tumbleweeds!

436
00:20:14,889 --> 00:20:16,015
Piney Woods!

437
00:20:16,056 --> 00:20:17,182
Hey, Piney, Piney

438
00:20:17,224 --> 00:20:18,919
did you come here
from Queens City

439
00:20:18,959 --> 00:20:19,926
on horseback?

440
00:20:19,960 --> 00:20:22,326
No, partner,
I flew.

441
00:20:22,363 --> 00:20:24,058
Hey, it's Red Traphagan!

442
00:20:32,907 --> 00:20:35,000
What's up, Arthur?

443
00:20:35,042 --> 00:20:36,009
Damn if I know.

444
00:20:36,043 --> 00:20:37,374
You know I'd tell
you if I knew.

445
00:20:37,411 --> 00:20:38,878
It smells the same.

446
00:20:38,913 --> 00:20:40,039
It stinks!

447
00:20:40,080 --> 00:20:42,310
Human perspiration smells,
it doesn't stink.

448
00:20:42,349 --> 00:20:44,214
Wouldn't have it
any other way, huh?

449
00:20:44,251 --> 00:20:45,218
Arthur.

450
00:20:45,252 --> 00:20:47,049
How are you?

451
00:20:47,087 --> 00:20:49,214
Jesus, you've been
having a great year.

452
00:20:49,256 --> 00:20:50,382
Best year of my life.

453
00:20:50,424 --> 00:20:52,551
I've bet you got
no reception like this

454
00:20:52,593 --> 00:20:53,560
in San Francisco.

455
00:20:53,594 --> 00:20:55,152
No, they pray I
don't show for class.

456
00:20:55,196 --> 00:20:56,561
What's up, Red?
Why are you here?

457
00:20:56,597 --> 00:20:57,894
Let's get a statement.

458
00:20:57,932 --> 00:20:58,899
Ponce!

459
00:20:58,933 --> 00:21:00,525
Ponce, I want to talk
to my boys, huh?

460
00:21:00,568 --> 00:21:02,229
Why is he here, Dutch?
What's happening?

461
00:21:02,336 --> 00:21:03,462
- Is he going to play?
- Never.

462
00:21:03,504 --> 00:21:05,062
He's here to coach
the catching

463
00:21:05,105 --> 00:21:06,732
and Piney's here to
catch the catching

464
00:21:06,774 --> 00:21:07,798
in case anything happens.

465
00:21:07,842 --> 00:21:09,036
You'll get your story later.

466
00:21:09,076 --> 00:21:10,543
- Why now?
- Mental lapse, that's why.

467
00:21:10,578 --> 00:21:11,704
Beat it.

468
00:21:11,745 --> 00:21:14,009
Look, there's lemonade,
there's cookies outside.

469
00:21:14,048 --> 00:21:15,572
Why don't you get going,
stay outside.

470
00:21:15,616 --> 00:21:16,583
If you want a story

471
00:21:16,617 --> 00:21:18,084
I'll give it to you later on.

472
00:21:18,118 --> 00:21:19,244
Where's your gun?

473
00:21:19,286 --> 00:21:20,583
Well, right here, partner.

474
00:21:20,621 --> 00:21:21,747
Hand it over.

475
00:21:21,789 --> 00:21:23,916
I'm in no mood to
see anybody get killed

476
00:21:23,958 --> 00:21:25,118
by a bullet wound.

477
00:21:25,159 --> 00:21:27,559
Piney, I hear you had
bullets with it, too.

478
00:21:27,595 --> 00:21:29,529
Well, yes, sir.
They're in the gun.

479
00:21:29,563 --> 00:21:31,360
Why the hell didn't
you tell me?

480
00:21:31,398 --> 00:21:33,161
Why, I didn't think
it'd go off.

481
00:21:33,200 --> 00:21:34,565
I'm always very careful.

482
00:21:34,602 --> 00:21:36,069
That's what everybody says.

483
00:21:36,103 --> 00:21:38,537
That's why the hospitals
are full of babies.

484
00:21:38,572 --> 00:21:40,369
- Jonah?
- Yeah.

485
00:21:40,407 --> 00:21:42,204
You shot guns in the war.

486
00:21:42,243 --> 00:21:43,870
No, sir, I played baseball.

487
00:21:43,911 --> 00:21:45,208
Some hell of a war.

488
00:21:45,246 --> 00:21:46,213
Canada.

489
00:21:46,247 --> 00:21:47,373
Yes, sir.

490
00:21:47,414 --> 00:21:48,972
- You shot guns in Vietnam.
- Right.

491
00:21:49,016 --> 00:21:50,881
Here. Take and empty this gun.

492
00:21:50,918 --> 00:21:52,215
Why am I here, Arthur?

493
00:21:52,253 --> 00:21:54,312
Boys? Boys...

494
00:21:54,355 --> 00:21:57,222
I want to welcome Red back
from the Coast

495
00:21:57,324 --> 00:22:00,521
to bolster us
and steady up the instruction.

496
00:22:01,929 --> 00:22:05,831
I want to welcome Piney Woods
back from the wild, wild west

497
00:22:05,866 --> 00:22:08,357
to ride along with us
all the way now

498
00:22:08,402 --> 00:22:09,391
is what I'm hoping.

499
00:22:14,108 --> 00:22:17,669
You've all been doing
very good jobs.

500
00:22:17,711 --> 00:22:21,511
Maybe now and then
some baseball player

501
00:22:21,549 --> 00:22:27,181
or other type of person gets
the idea that I'm not human.

502
00:22:27,221 --> 00:22:31,385
Well, for eXample, even...
Pearson here thought

503
00:22:31,425 --> 00:22:33,188
that I sometimes
wasn't human.

504
00:22:33,227 --> 00:22:34,387
No, sir.

505
00:22:36,897 --> 00:22:39,627
I, uh, probably ate
you out now and then

506
00:22:39,667 --> 00:22:41,532
but never
without a reason.

507
00:22:41,569 --> 00:22:45,198
No, sir, you only ate me out
for doing dumb things.

508
00:22:45,239 --> 00:22:46,729
No, no, no, no,
I ate you out

509
00:22:46,774 --> 00:22:48,036
for the good of the club

510
00:22:48,075 --> 00:22:50,202
and for your own pocketbook

511
00:22:50,244 --> 00:22:53,213
never for
anything personal

512
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:56,215
because I know
that you know

513
00:22:56,250 --> 00:22:58,684
that personally
I never had anything

514
00:22:58,719 --> 00:23:02,211
but the greatest respect
for you as a human being.

515
00:23:02,256 --> 00:23:04,747
Yes, sir,
that was how I always felt.

516
00:23:07,261 --> 00:23:09,092
When I die...

517
00:23:12,099 --> 00:23:14,590
When I die...

518
00:23:17,938 --> 00:23:20,930
...the papers will write
in the headlines

519
00:23:20,975 --> 00:23:24,968
"Son of a Bitches of the World
Have Lost Their Leader."

520
00:23:25,012 --> 00:23:27,947
Yet, many a boy
might shed a tear or two

521
00:23:27,982 --> 00:23:31,179
that rode along with me
into the big bunny

522
00:23:31,218 --> 00:23:33,778
and, uh, that's why
I maybe now and then

523
00:23:33,821 --> 00:23:36,847
I ate Pearson out or
some other type of person.

524
00:23:36,890 --> 00:23:38,357
It's time, Dutch.

525
00:23:38,392 --> 00:23:39,689
Yeah.

526
00:23:39,727 --> 00:23:41,524
I'll say it's time!

527
00:23:41,562 --> 00:23:42,790
Let's go, boys!

528
00:23:47,901 --> 00:23:49,027
Now that you're here

529
00:23:49,069 --> 00:23:50,536
tell me what you see, okay?

530
00:23:50,571 --> 00:23:52,038
'Cause I know I got faults.

